Features of react ->
1. component based architecture : reusable ui components
2. Virtual Dom : when state of an object changes, it updates the virtual dom first
3. Declarative UI -> updates UI when the right compoment changes
4. JSX -> syntax extension, helps write html in java script

react : npx create-react-app my-app

after installing the node using homebrew/brew 
cd my-app
in this we do : npm start -> this will start the development server

/src/create a new welcome.js

in welcome.js ->
import React from 'react'

function Welcome(props){
  return <h1>Hello, {props.name}!</h1>;
}
export default Welcome;


App.js ->
import React from 'react';
import Welcome from './Welcome';

function App() {
  return (
    <div>
      <Welcome name="Neeraj" />
      <Welcome name="Bob" />
      <Welcome name="Charlie" />
    </div>
  );
}

export default App;

App
 └─ div
     ├─ Welcome(name="Neeraj")
     ├─ Welcome(name="Bob")
     └─ Welcome(name="Charlie")


Understanding how clock works ->
import React , {Compoment } from 'react';
class Clock extends Compoments{
    constructor(props) {
        super(props);
        this.state = {date: new Date() };
    }

    componentDidMount() {
        this.timerID = setInterval(() => this.tick(), 1000);
    }

    componentWillUnmount(){
        clearInterval(this.timerID);
    }

    tick() {
        this.setState({
        date : new Date()
        });
    }

    render() {
        return(
            <div>
                <h1>Hello, world!</h1>
                <h2>It is {this.state.date.toLocaleTimeString()}.</h2>
            </div>
        );
    }
}

export default Clock;

Explanation :
extends Component → Clock inherits features from React’s Component class.

constructor(props) { super(props); this.state = {date: new Date()}; }
Constructor initializes the component.
super(props) calls the parent class constructor, required in React class components.
this.state = { date: new Date() } initializes a state object.
state holds data that can change over time.
Here, date is the current date and time.

4️⃣ componentDidMount() { this.timerID = setInterval(() => this.tick(), 1000); }
componentDidMount is a lifecycle method that runs after the component is inserted into the DOM.
setInterval(() => this.tick(), 1000) → calls the tick() method every 1 second.
this.timerID stores the interval ID so we can clear it later.

5️⃣ componentWillUnmount() { clearInterval(this.timerID); }
componentWillUnmount runs just before the component is removed from the DOM.
clearInterval(this.timerID) stops the timer to prevent memory leaks.

6️⃣ tick() { this.setState({ date: new Date() }); }
tick updates the state every second.
this.setState(...) tells React to re-render the component with the new state.
date: new Date() → updates the time.

7️⃣ render() { return ( ... ); }
render is a required method in class components.
Returns JSX (HTML-like code) that will appear in the browser.

















